HEADWORD: Galbanum
<hw>Gal"ba*num</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw>
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>galbanum</ets>, Gr. <?/, prob. from Heb.
<ets>klekb'n<?/h</ets>: cf. F. <ets>galbanum</ets>.]</ety> <def>A gum
resin exuding from the stems of certain Asiatic umbelliferous plants,
mostly species of <gen>Ferula</gen>. The <spn>Bubon Galbanum</spn> of
South Africa furnishes an inferior kind of galbanum. It has an acrid,
bitter taste, a strong, unpleasant smell, and is used for medical
purposes, also in the arts, as in the manufacture of varnish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Galbe</ent>⟦br⟧
